attackBuilder_appendAttack_description:
Append Attacks group runs attacks to check the shortest passwords first, then runs the same attacks to check increasingly longer passwords.

 When Append Attacks group is not enabled, Passware Kit checks all the passwords of each attack before running the next attack.
attackBuilder_attackListIsEmpty: To start customizing the password recovery settings, click the “Add Attack...” button and choose the password recovery attacks in accordance with the information about the missing password.
attackBuilder_bruteForce_description: Brute-force Attack checks all combinations of characters according to the current attack settings. This is the slowest, but most thorough, method.
attackBuilder_dictionary_description: Dictionary Attack checks thousands of words from dictionary files as possible passwords. Every word from the dictionary is tested in a variety of modifications according to the current attack settings.
attackBuilder_errors_noPasswordsToCheck: No passwords are covered by current settings
attackBuilder_joinAttacks_description: Join Attacks group applies its attacks to different parts of the password. Set the whole password length first. Then add attacks to the Join Attacks group for each part of the password.
attackBuilder_joinAttacks_example: Example: For password like "green123", set the following Join Attacks group:
attackBuilder_knownPassword_description:
Known Passwords/Part attack checks password(s) entered in the "Passwords to check" field. There is no need to open a file or create a custom dictionary to determine whether a password from the list of possible passwords is correct.

This attack can be combined with other attacks using the "Join Attacks" option. For example, if the password is known to be a word followed by "1980", use Join Attacks to combine Dictionary attack and Known Passwords/Part attack with the value set to "1980".
attackBuilder_knownPassword_tooltip:
To insert special symbols, use the following syntax rules:  
\\0 - 0x00 (null)  
\\a - 0x07 (bell)  
\\b - 0x08 (backspace)  
\\t - 0x09 (tab)  
\\n - 0x0A (new line)  
\\v - 0x0B (vertical tab)  
\\f - 0x0C (form feed)  
\\r - 0x0D (carriage return)  
\\* - asterisk (just \* is fine too)  
\\? - question mark (just ? is fine too)  
\\\\ - slash
attackBuilder_knownPassword_value: Password(s) to check. One per line.
attackBuilder_loadPopup_message: Overwrite attack settings or add attack to the list?
attackBuilder_mask_description: Mask Attack checks passwords that match a specified pattern or mask.
attackBuilder_previousPasswords_descript: Previous Passwords Attack checks passwords that were previously recovered by other attacks for other files. It automatically saves all passwords found.
attackBuilder_xieve_description: Xieve Attack checks only those combinations of characters that are common in the specified language. It dramatically boosts Brute-Force Attack speed by skipping nonsensical combinations of characters.
attack_memoryKeysAttackDescr:
If there is a memory image of a computer, acquired while this file was open, the Encryption Keys Extraction Attack instantly extracts the encryption keys from the memory image and decrypts the file, regardless of the password length.

Please specify the memory image or the system hibernation file (hiberfil.sys) for this attack.
attack_rainbow_description:
Below is the list of rainbow tables available for the attack.

For MS Office files up to v.2003 you can use the tables from [Passware Rainbow Tables for Office](https://www.passware.com/passware-office-rainbow-tables/). For password hashes you can download rainbow tables at third-party websites, such as [www.FreeRainbowTables.com](https://freerainbowtables.com/). Then add the downloaded tables to the list.
attack_sureZipDescr: SureZip Attack decrypts most WinZip archives in less than an hour regardless of their passwords. At least five simultaneously encrypted files are required in order to process the archive. Archives created with WinZip are supported.
attack_zipPlaintextDescr:
If there is at least one file from a password protected Zip archive available unencrypted, the Zip Plaintext Attack instantly decrypts the whole archive for you, regardless of the password length.

Please compress the known file with the same version of Zip and then apply it to the Zip Plaintext Attack as a Plaintext archive.

disks_veracrypt_help_pim:
Personal Iterations Multiplier (PIM) is a parameter that controls the number of iterations used by the header key derivation function.  
If no PIM value is specified or PIM is 0, the default number of VeraCrypt iterations will be used.  
For short passwords, 19 characters or less, the minimum PIM value is 98 for system encryption and 485 for non-system encryption and files containers.

For password with 20 characters and more the minimum PIM value is 1.

passwordExchangePostInstallScreen_footer: You can enable or disable this option at any time at **Tools | Options | Password Exchange**.
passwordExchange_brief:
Password Exchange provides access to the list of passwords found by Passware Kit users worldwide, offering it as an advanced dictionary to improve chances of finding strong passwords.

This is an opt-in service available for Passware Kit Forensic customers only.

Optional Manual Sync mode allows one to use Password Exchange in air-gapped environments.

In this mode, a human-readable text file (JSON) may be copied to a computer that has Internet access to export passwords to the Passware server and import new passwords from the Passware database to the computer running Passware Kit.

Learn more at: [https://www.passware.com/password-exchange/](https://www.passware.com/password-exchange/)
